codex
The new repin pipeline currently admits mislabeled gold examples for key memory classes, and the Mem0 local baseline is configured to leak state across runs. In addition, the new validity guard is not enforced on the runtime path, so the original empty-class failure mode can still slip through on future rebuilds.

Full review comments:

- [P1] Reject repinned queries that don't satisfy the target class — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/python/eval/gold_repin.py:183-189
  `augment_class()` only checks that `required_evidence` is non-empty, so it accepts `multi_session`/`knowledge_update` outputs that are answerable from a single document. The checked-in gold already contains such cases (for example `d0a-0441` and `d0a-0235`), even though the real LongMemEval gold for those classes always spans multiple sessions. That means Slice 10 will score plain single-session questions as `multi_session`/`knowledge_update`, biasing the parity numbers for the very classes this repin is meant to repair.

- [P1] Avoid reusing a persistent Mem0 collection across eval runs — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/python/eval/mem0_local.py:39-40
  The default Mem0 config points every run at the same on-disk Chroma collection (`/tmp/mem0_chroma`, `r2_eval`), while the adapter also uses a fixed `user_id`. Re-running the parity harness on a different corpus or branch will therefore reopen the previous collection and search stale memories from earlier runs, making the Mem0 baseline non-reproducible unless operators manually wipe `/tmp/mem0_chroma` first.

- [P2] Enforce the new corpus-validity guard before running repinned evals — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/python/eval/r2_parity_eval.py:579-592
  `load_repin_gold()` only checks for a non-empty `corpus_hash` and at least one query, but this slice's new `validate_repin()` guard is never called on the runtime path. If a rebuild produces an underfilled class (for example via `--no-augment` or a stale checkpoint), `R2Harness.from_repin_gold()` will still run and `run()` will quietly emit 0/`null` for the missing classes—recreating the Slice-25 `N=0` failure mode that this change set is supposed to prevent.
